  "prompt": "I started doing USMLE after my MBBS studied 2 years at home then stopped, now after 2 more years can I start it again? I want to apply in psychiatry?",
  "response": "Yes, you can definitely resume your USMLE preparation after a break. Many people take time off due to various circumstances, and it\u2019s not uncommon to return to studying after a gap. Here are some steps you can follow to get back on track:\n\n1. **Create a Study Plan**: Assess how much time you have until you want to take the exams and create a realistic study schedule. Consider reviewing material you covered previously and planning for any new content.\n\n2. **Review Resources**: Gather relevant study materials, such as First Aid for the USMLE Step 1, UWorld question bank, and relevant videos. Refresh your knowledge with resources that you find most helpful.\n\n3. **Take Practice Exams**: Consider taking a practice exam to assess your current level of knowledge and identify areas that need more focus.\n\n4. **Stay Consistent**: Set up a daily study routine that includes dedicated time for reading, practice questions, and self-assessment.\n\n5. **Connect with Others**: Joining study groups or forums can be very helpful. Engaging with others preparing for the same exams can provide motivation and support.\n\n6. **Focus on Psychiatry**: Since you plan to apply in psychiatry, ensure you pay attention to the topics relevant to that specialty as you study.\n\n7. **Stay Informed**: Keep an eye on any changes regarding the USMLE processes, scoring, and residency application timelines that might have occurred during your time away.\n\nFinally, once you feel prepared, you can register for the USMLE exams and proceed with your application to residency programs in psychiatry. Good luck with your studies and future career!",
